'''''United States v. Rehlander''''' was a 2011 case heard in the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit]]. It struck down a [[Maine]] law providing that temporary commitment triggered automatic revocation of a patient's [[firearms license]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/02/new-york-disarms-the-mentally-ill#.yRG6gOZpU|title=New York Disarms the ‘Mentally Ill’|first1=James B.|last1=Jacobs|first2=Zoe|last2=Fuhr|work=The Marshall Project|date=December 2, 2015|accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>{{Dubious |reason=  Actually the court found that "temporary hospitalization under section 3863 does not constitute a "commitment" under section 922 — just as it clearly does not constitute a commitment under Maine law itself"|date=September 2016}}

The court held that the firearms ban could only apply to individuals who had received [[due process]] through a judicial hearing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/01/18/politics/how-does-maine-balance-public-safety-and-gun-rights-of-mentally-ill/|work=Bangor Daily News|title=How does Maine balance public safety and gun rights of mentally ill?|first=Robert|last=Long|date=January 18, 2013|accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>

